description: An extremely rare Australian self-published comic from the 1940s. Quoting Danny Best, "You just don’t see these kinds of comic books anymore, so here we go. This issue of Desert Dragon Comic first appeared in April 1946 and has been sought after ever since, being, as it is, one of the earliest self-published Australian comics known. Written and drawn by George T.C. Hubble, better known as Tom Hubble, aka Hub, the story is a simple one, as the bulk of comic books were at the time. Keeping in with Hubble’s tendency to use comic books as an education tool, the strip is full of facts and figures, with one pertinent fact written down the side of the strip, as Dr Mensana finds himself in a world loaded with living dinosaurs and even though Dr Mensana gains his powers from a drug, he reminds the readers that, “Stimulants are harmful,”. This is truly a comic book loaded with messages. Dr Mensana was one of Hubble’s original creations." (See Best's blog on this subject, http://ohdannyboy.blogspot.com/2012/11/desert-dragon-comic-by-hub-rare-1946.html .)
name: Desert Dragon

description:
Douwe Dabbert and his knapsack always get into adventures. He doesn't mean to, he likes things to be orderly but faith decides differently.

From 1975 to 2001 these stories ran in consecutive issues of the Dutch/Belgian weekly Donald Duck magazine.

All issues exist as soft cover (no white edges) and hard cover (white edges beyond the orange line). The total run of 23 issues have been collected in the Douwe Dabbert Collectie from Lecturama Uitgeverij.
name: De Avonturen van Douwe Dabbert
